# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: allose
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:allose/acarbose] Acarbose is a starch blocker that works by inhibiting alpha glucosidase, an intestinal enzyme that releases glucose from larger carbohydrates such as starch and sucrose.
[src:allose/acarbose] It is composed of an acarviosin moiety with a maltose at the reducing terminus.
[src:allose/acarbose] Acarbose is inexpensive and popular in China, but not in the U.S.
[src:allose/acarbose] One physician explains that U.S. use is limited, because it is not potent enough to offset side effects of diarrhea and flatulence.
[src:allose/acarbose] In type II diabetic patients, acarbose averages an absolute decrease of 0.8 percentage points in HbA1c, which is a decrease of about 10% in typical HbA1c values in diabetes studies.
[src:allose/acarbose] Individuals with higher baseline levels show higher reductions, about an 0.12% additional decrease for each point of baseline HbA1c.
[src:allose/acarbose] Its effect on postprandial glucose, but not on HbA1c, scales with dose.
[src:allose/acarbose] Among diabetic patients, acarbose may help reduce the damage done to blood vessels and kidneys by reducing glucose levels.
[src:allose/acarbose] A Cochrane systematic review assessed the effect of alpha-glucosidase inhibitors in people with prediabetes, defined as impaired glucose tolerance, impaired fasting blood glucose, elevated glycated hemoglobin A1c (HbA1c).
[src:allose/acarbose] Several studies showed that glucosidase inhibitors and alpha-amylase inhibitors promote loss of visceral fat and waist by acting as calorie restriction mimetics (linked to their acarbose-like action).
[src:allose/acarbose] The combination of acarbose with metformin results in greater reductions of HbA1c, fasting blood glucose and post-prandial glucose than either agent alone.
[src:allose/acarbose] Since acarbose prevents the degradation of complex carbohydrates into glucose, some carbohydrate will remain in the intestine and be delivered to the colon.
[src:allose/acarbose] In the colon, bacteria digest (ferment) the complex carbohydrates, causing gastrointestinal side-effects such as flatulence (78% of patients) and diarrhea (14% of patients).
[src:allose/acarbose] Since these effects are dose-related, in general it is advised to start with a low dose and gradually increase the dose to the desired amount.
[src:allose/acarbose] One study found that gastrointestinal side effects decreased significantly (from 50% to 15%) over 24 weeks, even on constant dosing.
[src:allose/acarbose] Sucrose is more likely to trigger GI side effects compared to starch.
[src:allose/acarbose] Acarbose is associated with very rare elevated transaminases (19 out of 500,000).
[src:allose/acarbose] Even rarer cases of hepatitis has been reported with acarbose use.
[src:allose/acarbose] It usually goes away when the medicine is stopped.
[src:allose/acarbose] Liver enzymes should be checked before and during use of this medicine as a precaution.
[src:allose/acarbose] A 2016 meta-analysis confirms that alpha-glucosidase inhibitors, including acarbose, have a statistically significant link to elevated transaminase levels.
[src:allose/acarbose] Acarbose inhibits enzymes (glycoside hydrolases) needed to digest carbohydrates, specifically, alpha-glucosidase enzymes in the brush border of the small intestines, and pancreatic alpha-amylase.
[src:allose/acarbose] It locks up the enzymes by mimicking the transition state of the substrate with its amine linkage.
[src:allose/acarbose] However, bacterial alpha-amylases from gut microbiome are able to degrade acarbose.
[src:allose/acarbose] Pancreatic alpha-amylase hydrolyzes complex starches to oligosaccharides in the lumen of the small intestine, whereas the membrane-bound intestinal alpha-glucosidases hydrolyze oligosaccharides, trisaccharides, and disaccharides to glucose and other monosaccharides in the small intestine.
[src:allose/acarbose] Inhibition of these enzyme systems reduces the rate of digestion of complex carbohydrates.
[src:allose/acarbose] Less glucose is absorbed because the carbohydrates are not broken down into glucose molecules.
[src:allose/acarbose] In diabetic patients, the short-term effect of these drug therapies is to decrease current blood glucose levels; the long-term effect is a reduction in HbA1c level.
[src:allose/acarbose] Acarbose degradation is the unique feature of glycoside hydrolases in gut microbiota, acarbose degrading glucosidase, which hydrolyze acarbose into an acarviosine-glucose and glucose.
[src:allose/acarbose] Human enzymes do transform acarbose: the pancreatic alpha-amylase is able to perform a rearrangement reaction, moving the glucose unit in the "tail" maltose to the "head" of the molecule.
[src:allose/acarbose] Analog drugs with the "tail" glucose removed or flipped to an α(1-6) linkage resist this transformation.
[src:allose/acarbose] It has been reported that the maltogenic alpha-amylase from *Thermus* sp.
[src:allose/acarbose] IM6501 (ThMA) and a cyclodextrinase (CDase) from *Streptococcus pyogenes* could hydrolyse acarbose to glucose and acarviosine-glucose, ThMA can further hydrolyze acarviosine-glucose into acarviosin and glucose.
[src:allose/acarbose] A cyclomaltodextrinase (CDase) from gut bacteria *Lactobacillus plantarum* degraded acarbose via two different modes of action to produce maltose and acarviosin, as well as glucose and acarviosine-glucose, suggest that acarbose resistance is caused by the human microbiome.
[src:allose/acarbose] The microbiome-derived acarbose kinases are also specific to phosphorylate and inactivate acarbose.
[src:allose/acarbose] The molecular modeling showed the interaction between gut bacterial acarbose degrading glucosidase and human α-amylase.
[src:allose/acarbose] In nature, acarbose is synthesized by soil bacteria *Actinoplanes sp* through its precursor valienamine.
[src:allose/acarbose] Acarbose is described chemically as a pseudotetrasaccharide, specifically a maltotetraose mimic inhibitor.
[src:allose/acarbose] As an inhibitor that mimics some natural substrates, it is useful for elucidating the structure of sugar-digesting enzymes, by binding into the same pocket.
[src:allose/acarbose] Most studies investigating alpha-glucosidase and alpha-amylase inhibitory activity use acarbose as reference.
[src:allose/acarbose] In human T2DM patients, acarbose reduces total triglyceride levels.
[src:allose/acarbose] Acarbose has a similar effect in non-T2DM patients with isolated familial hypertriglyceridemia.
[src:allose/acarbose] In smaller samples of healthy human volunteers, acarbose increases postprandial GLP-1 levels.
[src:allose/acarbose] In studies conducted by three independent laboratories by the US National Institute on Aging's intervention testing programme, acarbose was shown to extend the lifespan of female mice by 5% and of male mice by 22%.
[src:allose/acarbose] A pooled analysis of data from 10 observational studies show that acarbose appears to reduce body weight irrespective of glycemic control in diabetic patients.
[src:allose/acarbose] The effect is more pronounced in patients of the female sex, South East Asian and East Asian ethnicity, younger age, higher body mass index, short duration of diabetes, or no previous treatment.
[src:allose/aldohexose] In chemistry, a **hexose** is a monosaccharide (simple sugar) with six carbon atoms.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The chemical formula for all hexoses is C6H12O6, and their molecular weight is 180.156 g/mol.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Hexoses exist in two forms, open-chain or cyclic, that easily convert into each other in aqueous solutions.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The open-chain form of a hexose, which usually is favored in solutions, has the general structure H−(CHOH)*n*−1−C(=O)−(CHOH)6−*n*−H, where *n* is 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Namely, five of the carbons have one hydroxyl functional group (−OH) each, connected by a single bond, and one has an oxo group (=O), forming a carbonyl group (C=O).
[src:allose/aldohexose] The remaining bonds of the carbon atoms are satisfied by seven hydrogen atoms.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The carbons are commonly numbered 1 to 6 starting at the end closest to the carbonyl.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Hexoses are extremely important in biochemistry, both as isolated molecules (such as glucose and fructose) and as building blocks of other compounds such as starch, cellulose, and glycosides.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Hexoses can form dihexose (like sucrose) by a condensation reaction that makes 1,6-glycosidic bond.
[src:allose/aldohexose] When the carbonyl is in position 1, forming a formyl group (−CH=O), the sugar is called an **aldohexose**, a special case of aldose.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Otherwise, if the carbonyl position is 2 or 3, the sugar is a derivative of a ketone, and is called a **ketohexose**, a special case of ketose; specifically, an ***n*-ketohexose**.
[src:allose/aldohexose] However, the 3-ketohexoses have not been observed in nature, and are difficult to synthesize; so the term "ketohexose" usually means 2-ketohexose.
[src:allose/aldohexose] In the linear form, there are 16 aldohexoses and eight 2-ketohexoses, stereoisomers that differ in the spatial position of the hydroxyl groups.
[src:allose/aldohexose] These species occur in pairs of optical isomers.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Each pair has a conventional name (like "glucose" or "fructose"), and the two members are labeled "D-" or "L-", depending on whether the hydroxyl in position 5, in the Fischer projection of the molecule, is to the right or to the left of the axis, respectively.
[src:allose/aldohexose] These labels are independent of the optical activity of the isomers.
[src:allose/aldohexose] In general, only one of the two enantiomers occurs naturally (for example, D-glucose) and can be metabolized by animals or fermented by yeasts.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The term "hexose" sometimes is assumed to include **deoxyhexoses**, such as fucose and rhamnose: compounds with general formula C6H12O6−*y* that can be described as derived from hexoses by replacement of one or more hydroxyl groups with hydrogen atoms.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The aldohexoses are a subclass of the hexoses which, in the linear form, have the carbonyl at carbon 1, forming an aldehyde derivative with structure H−C(=O)−(CHOH)5−H.
[src:allose/aldohexose] In linear form, an aldohexose has four chiral centres, which give 16 possible aldohexose stereoisomers (24), comprising 8 pairs of enantiomers.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Of these D-isomers, all except D-altrose occur in living organisms, but only three are common: D-glucose, D-galactose, and D-mannose.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The L-isomers are generally absent in living organisms; however, L-altrose has been isolated from strains of the bacterium *Butyrivibrio fibrisolvens*.
[src:allose/aldohexose] When drawn in this order, the Fischer projections of the D-aldohexoses can be identified with the 3-digit binary numbers from 0 to 7, namely 000, 001, 010, 011, 100, 101, 110, 111.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The three bits, from left to right, indicate the position of the hydroxyls on carbons 4, 3, and 2, respectively: to the right if the bit value is 0, and to the left if the value is 1.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The Fischer diagrams of the eight L-aldohexoses are the mirror images of the corresponding D-isomers; with all hydroxyls reversed, including the one on carbon 5.
[src:allose/aldohexose] A ketohexose is a ketone-containing hexose.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The important ketohexoses are the 2-ketohexoses, and the most important 2-ketose is fructose.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Besides the 2-ketoses, there are only the 3-Ketoses, and they do not exist in nature, although at least one 3-ketohexose has been synthesized, with great difficulty.
[src:allose/aldohexose] In the linear form, the 2-ketohexoses have three chiral centers and therefore eight possible stereoisomers (23), comprising four pairs of enantiomers.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The corresponding L forms have the hydroxyls on carbons 3, 4, and 5 reversed.
[src:allose/aldohexose] In theory, the ketohexoses include also the 3-ketohexoses, which have the carbonyl in position 3; namely H−(CHOH)2−C(=O)−(CHOH)3−H.
[src:allose/aldohexose] However, these compounds are not known to occur in nature, and are difficult to synthesize.
[src:allose/aldohexose] In 1897, an unfermentable product obtained by treatment of fructose with bases, in particular lead(II) hydroxide, was given the name *glutose*, a portmanteau of *glucose* and *fructose*, and was claimed to be a 3-ketohexose.
[src:allose/aldohexose] However, subsequent studies showed that the substance was a mixture of various other compounds.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The unequivocal synthesis and isolation of a 3-ketohexose, *xylo*-3-hexulose, through a rather complex route, was first reported in 1961 by George U.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Like most monosaccharides with five or more carbons, each aldohexose or 2-ketohexose also exists in one or more cyclic (closed-chain) forms, derived from the open-chain form by an internal rearrangement between the carbonyl group and one of the hydroxyl groups.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The reaction turns the =O group into a hydroxyl, and the hydroxyl into an ether bridge (−O−) between the two carbon atoms, thus creating a ring with one oxygen atom and four or five carbons.
[src:allose/aldohexose] If the cycle has five carbon atoms (six atoms in total), the closed form is called a pyranose, after the cyclic ether tetrahydropyran, that has the same ring.
[src:allose/aldohexose] If the cycle has four carbon atoms (five in total), the form is called furanose after the compound tetrahydrofuran.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The conventional numbering of the carbons in the closed form is the same as in the open-chain form.
[src:allose/aldohexose] If the sugar is an aldohexose, with the carbonyl in position 1, the reaction may involve the hydroxyl on carbon 4 or carbon 5, creating a hemiacetal with five- or six-membered ring, respectively.
[src:allose/aldohexose] If the sugar is a 2-ketohexose, it can only involve the hydroxyl in carbon 5, and will create a hemiketal with a five-membered ring.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The closure turns the carboxyl carbon into a chiral center, which may have either of two configurations, depending on the position of the new hydroxyl.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Therefore, each hexose in linear form can produce two distinct closed forms, identified by prefixes "α" and "β".
[src:allose/aldohexose] It has been known since 1926 that hexoses in the crystalline solid state assume the cyclic form.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The "α" and "β" forms, which are not enantiomers, will usually crystallize separately as distinct species.
[src:allose/aldohexose] For example, D-glucose forms an α crystal that has specific rotation of +112° and melting point of 146 °C, as well as a β crystal that has specific rotation of +19° and melting point of 150 °C.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The linear form does not crystallize, and exists only in small amounts in water solutions, where it is in equilibrium with the closed forms.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Nevertheless, it plays an essential role as the intermediate stage between those closed forms.
[src:allose/aldohexose] In particular, the "α" and "β" forms can convert to into each other by returning to the open-chain form and then closing in the opposite configuration.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Although all hexoses have similar structures and share some general properties, each enantiomer pair has its own chemistry.
[src:allose/aldohexose] Fructose is soluble in water, alcohol, and ether.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The two enantiomers of each pair generally have vastly different biological properties.
[src:allose/aldohexose] 2-Ketohexoses are stable over a wide pH range, and with a primary p*K*a of 10.28, will only deprotonate at high pH, so are marginally less stable than aldohexoses in solution.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The aldohexose that is most important in biochemistry is D-glucose, which is the main "fuel" for metabolism in many living organisms.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The 2-ketohexoses psicose, fructose and tagatose occur naturally as the D-isomers, whereas sorbose occurs naturally as the L-isomer.
[src:allose/aldohexose] D-Sorbose is commonly used in the commercial synthesis of ascorbic acid.
[src:allose/aldohexose] D-Tagatose is a rare natural ketohexose that is found in small quantities in food.
[src:allose/aldohexose] D-Fructose is responsible for the sweet taste of many fruits, and is a building block of sucrose, the common sugar.
[src:allose/aldohexose] The term "hexose" may sometimes be used to include the deoxyhexoses, which have one or more hydroxyls (−OH) replaced by hydrogen atoms (−H).
[src:allose/aldohexose] It is named as the parent hexose, with the prefix "*x*-deoxy-", the *x* indicating the carbon with the affected hydroxyl.
[src:allose/aldose] An **aldose** is a monosaccharide (a simple sugar) with a carbon backbone chain with a carbonyl group on the endmost carbon atom, making it an aldehyde, and hydroxyl groups connected to all the other carbon atoms.
[src:allose/aldose] Aldoses can be distinguished from ketoses, which have the carbonyl group away from the end of the molecule, and are therefore ketones.
[src:allose/aldose] Like most carbohydrates, simple aldoses have the general chemical formula C*n*(H2O)*n*.
[src:allose/aldose] Because formaldehyde (n=1) and glycolaldehyde (n=2) are not generally considered to be carbohydrates, the simplest possible aldose is the triose glyceraldehyde, which only contains three carbon atoms.
[src:allose/aldose] Because they have at least one asymmetric carbon center, all aldoses exhibit stereoisomerism.
[src:allose/aldose] Aldoses can exist in either a D- form or L- form.
[src:allose/aldose] The determination is made based on the chirality of the asymmetric carbon furthest from the aldehyde end, namely the second-last carbon in the chain.
[src:allose/aldose] Aldoses with alcohol groups on the right of the Fischer projection are D-aldoses, and those with alcohols on the left are L-aldoses.
[src:allose/aldose] D-aldoses are more common than L-aldoses in nature.
[src:allose/aldose] Examples of aldoses include glyceraldehyde, erythrose, ribose, glucose and galactose.
[src:allose/aldose] Ketoses and aldoses can be chemically differentiated through Seliwanoff's test, where the sample is heated with acid and resorcinol.
[src:allose/aldose] The test relies on the dehydration reaction which occurs more quickly in ketoses, so that while aldoses react slowly, producing a light pink color, ketoses react more quickly and strongly to produce a dark red color.
[src:allose/aldose] Aldoses can isomerize to ketoses through the Lobry-de Bruyn-van Ekenstein transformation.
[src:allose/aldose] Aldoses are differentiated by the number of carbon atoms in the main chain.
[src:allose/aldose] The minimum number of carbon atoms in a backbone needed to form a molecule that is still considered a carbohydrate is 3, and carbohydrates with three carbon atoms are called trioses.
[src:allose/aldose] The only aldotriose is glyceraldehyde, which has one chiral stereocenter with 2 possible enantiomers, D- and L-glyceraldehyde.
[src:allose/aldose] The most commonly discussed category of aldoses are those with six carbon atoms, aldohexoses.
[src:allose/aldose] Aldoses are commonly referred to by names specific to one stereoisomer of the compound.
[src:allose/aldose] This distinction is especially vital in biochemistry, as many systems can only use one enantiomer of the carbohydrate and not the other.
[src:allose/aldose] However, aldoses are not locked into any one conformation: they can and do fluctuate between different forms.
[src:allose/aldose] Aldoses can tautomerize to ketoses in a dynamic process with an enol intermediate (more specifically, an enediol).
[src:allose/aldose] This process is reversible, so aldoses and ketoses can be thought of as being in equilibrium with each other.
[src:allose/aldose] However, aldehydes and ketones are almost always more stable than the corresponding enol forms, so the aldo- and keto- forms normally predominate.
[src:allose/aldose] This process, with its enol intermediate, also allows stereoisomerization.
[src:allose/aldose] Basic solutions accelerate the interconversion of isomers.
[src:allose/aldose] Carbohydrates with more than four carbon atoms exist in an equilibrium between the closed ring, or cyclic form, and the open-chain form.
[src:allose/aldose] Cyclic aldoses are usually drawn as Haworth projections, and open chain forms are commonly drawn as Fischer projections, both of which represent important stereochemical information about the forms they depict.
[src:allose/allose] Reduction of allose by catalytic hydrogenation produces an obscure sugar alcohol allitol which is rarely used in the chemical industry.
[src:allose/altrose] The ring conformation of α-altropyranoside is flexible compared to most other aldohexopyranosides, with idose as exception.
[src:allose/altrose] In solution different derivatives of altrose have been shown to occupy both 4C1, OS2 and 1C4-conformations.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Plants store starch within specialized organelles called amyloplasts.
[src:allose/amylopectin] To generate energy, the plant hydrolyzes the starch, releasing the glucose subunits.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Humans and other animals that eat plant foods also use amylase, an enzyme that assists in breaking down amylopectin, to initiate the hydrolysis of starch.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Starch is made of about 70–80% amylopectin by weight, though it varies depending on the source.
[src:allose/amylopectin] For example, it ranges from lower percent content in long-grain rice, amylomaize, and russet potatoes to 100% in glutinous rice, waxy potato starch, and waxy corn.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin is highly branched, being formed of 2,000 to 200,000 glucose units.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Its inner chains are formed of 20–24 glucose subunits.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Dissolved amylopectin starch has a lower tendency of retrogradation (a partial recrystallization after cooking—a part of the staling process) during storage and cooling.
[src:allose/amylopectin] For this main reason, the waxy starches are used in different applications mainly as a thickening agent or stabilizer.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin is a key component in the crystallization of starch's final configuration, accounting for 70-80% of the final mass.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Composed of α-glucose, it is formed in plants as a primary measure of energy storage in tandem with this structural metric.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin bears a *straight/linear* chain along with a number of *side chains* which may be *branched* further.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Glucose units are linked in a linear way with α(1→4) glycosidic bonds.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Branching usually occurs at intervals of 25 residues.
[src:allose/amylopectin] At the places of origin of a side chain, the branching that takes place bears an α(1→6) glycosidic bond, resulting in a soluble molecule that can be quickly degraded as it has many end points onto which enzymes can attach.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Wolform and Thompson (1956) have also reported α(1→3)linkages in case of amylopectin.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin contains a larger number of glucose units (2000 to 200,000) as compared to amylose containing 200 to 1000 α-glucose units.
[src:allose/amylopectin] In contrast, amylose contains very few α(1→6) bonds, or even none at all.
[src:allose/amylopectin] This causes amylose to be hydrolyzed more slowly, but also creates higher density and insolubility.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin is divided into *A* and *B* helical chains of α-glucose.
[src:allose/amylopectin] *A* chains are chains that carry no other chains, resulting in an eventual terminus, whereas *B* chains are chains that do carry other chains, perpetuating the amylopectin polymer.
[src:allose/amylopectin] The ratio between these is usually between 0.8 and 1.4.
[src:allose/amylopectin] The formation of chain structures has a direct impact on the overall strength of the whole polymer; the longer a chain is, the more differing the effects amylopectin will have on starch's morphology.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Packing of chains, inter block chain length (IB-CL), also correlates with the gelatinization temperature of starch granules.
[src:allose/amylopectin] In tandem, the IB-CL will increase as the length of *B* chains increases, meaning that as the length of individual *B* chains increases, so does the blocks between connections with other chains.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Finally, in general, the more densely packed the resulting molecule of amylopectin, the higher the strength of the starch gel as a whole unit.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Starch utilizes the density-strength correlation of amylopectin as a measure of forming dense, strong bricks as a basis for the final starch configuration.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin in starch is formed into helices to compose hexagonal structures that will subsequently be differentiated into *A* (cereal) and *B* (high-amylose; tubular) type starch.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Structurally, *A* is more compact, while *B* is looser, hence the higher concentration of amylose.
[src:allose/amylopectin] The categorization of amylopectin began with the first observation in starch in 1716 by Antonie van Leeuwenhoek, where he differentiated starch into two fundamental structural components.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Since then and through the 1940s, research focused on various methods of separation, like fractional precipitation or enzymatically.
[src:allose/amylopectin] This gave rise to the Meyer definition of amylose and "reserv[ing] the name amylopectin to carbohydrates that are branched molecule, degraded by b-amylase only to the stage of residual dextrin".
[src:allose/amylopectin] Meyer also proposed the tree like structure model for amylopectin.
[src:allose/amylopectin] The currently accepted structural model was proposed in 1972, based on the cluster organization of double helical structures.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Other models have been proposed since, such as the Bertoft BB model, or building block and backbone model in 2012.
[src:allose/amylopectin] This model claims short chains are the structural building blocks and long chains the backbone to carry the building blocks, and that the different lengths of chain are separated by their position and direction of elongation.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Both the formation and degradation of amylopectin is important to the metabolic processes of organisms.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin is one of the two dominant components of starch, and starch is a successful storage molecule for energy.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Because of this, it is synthesized and broken down in most plants and cyanobacteria.
[src:allose/amylopectin] In fact, amylopectin seems to rival glycogen, the energy storage molecule in animals, because it is able to store more glucose units and henceforth more energy.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin is synthesized by the linkage of α(1→4) glycosidic bonds.
[src:allose/amylopectin] The extensive branching of amylopectin (α(1→6) glycosidic bond) is initiated by BE and this is what differentiates amylose from amylopectin.
[src:allose/amylopectin] DBE is also needed during this synthesis process to regulate the distribution of these branches.
[src:allose/amylopectin] The breakdown of amylopectin has been studied in context with the breakdown of starch in animals and humans.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Starch is mostly composed of amylopectin and amylose, but amylopectin has been shown to degrade more easily.
[src:allose/amylopectin] The reason is most likely because amylopectin is highly branched and these branches are more available to digestive enzymes.
[src:allose/amylopectin] In contrast, amylose tends to form helices and contain hydrogen bonding.
[src:allose/amylopectin] There are enzymes that are involved in the synthesis and degradation of amylopectin that have isoforms that display different relationships with proteins and other enzymes.
[src:allose/amylopectin] For example, there are many versions of SS (starch synthase).
[src:allose/amylopectin] Even the third isoform (SS-III) has two different versions.
[src:allose/amylopectin] It is believed that SS-I and SS-II both have a role in elongating the chains of amylopectin branches.
[src:allose/amylopectin] SS-IV is also thought to be responsible for the leaf-like structure of starch granule clusters.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin is the most common carbohydrate in the human diet and is contained in many staple foods.
[src:allose/amylopectin] The major sources of amylopectin of starch intake worldwide are the cereals such as rice, wheat, and maize, and the root vegetables potatoes and cassava.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Upon cooking, amylopectin in the starch is transformed into readily accessible glucose chains with very different nutritional and functional properties.
[src:allose/amylopectin] During cooking with high heat, sugars released from amylopectin can react with amino acids via the Maillard reaction, forming advanced glycation end-products (AGEs), contributing aromas, flavors and texture to foods.
[src:allose/amylopectin] The amylose/amylopectin ratio, molecular weight and molecular fine structure influences the physicochemical properties as well as energy release of different types of starches, which affects the number of calories people consume from food.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin is also sometimes used as a workout supplement due to this caloric density and a correlation with muscle protein synthesis.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Industrially, amylopectin is used as a stabilizer and thickener, such as corn starch.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin has also been widely used for the development of edible coating films because of its abundance, cost-effectiveness, and excellent film-forming abilities.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin-based films have good optical, organoleptic and gas barrier properties, however, they have poor mechanical properties.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Many attempts have been made to overcome these limitations, such as the addition of co-biopolymers or other secondary additives to improve the mechanical and tensile properties of the films.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Properties of the amylopectin-based films can be influenced by many factors, including types of starch, temperature and time during film formation, plasticizers, co-biopolymers, and storage conditions.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Historically, there is a long established use of starch in sizing applications for textiles.
[src:allose/amylopectin] As a component of starch, amylopectin is responsible for the retrogradation or crystalline reordering of the starch, which adds rigidity.
[src:allose/amylopectin] This stiffening effect is used for several textile industry processes, such as printing and pressing, to maintain the shape of a fabric over time.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin is also used as a sizing agent for yarns, to reinforce and protects the fibers from abrasion and breakage during weaving.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin has seen a rise of use in biomedical applications due to its physiological factors, ease of availability, and low cost.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Specifically, amylopectin has very advantageous biochemical properties due to its prevalence as a natural polysaccharide.
[src:allose/amylopectin] This causes a high sense of biocompatibility with cells and molecules within the body.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin is also able to biodegrade to a high degree due to its high sense of crosslinking with 1,6 glycosidic bonds.
[src:allose/amylopectin] The bonds easily broken down by the body can reduce molecular weight, expose certain regions, and interact certain bonds with clinical factors.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Various physical, chemical, and enzymatic methods of modification have also been researched for amylopectin.
[src:allose/amylopectin] These, generally, allow for enhanced and controllable properties which can be selected for the field of research performed.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin's main role, clinically, is within its integration in starch.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Function and structure of amylopectin is based on its integration with amylose and other bounded molecules.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Separating these molecules and isolated amylopectin is quite difficult for researchers to perform.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Drug delivery refers to technology used to present a drug to a pre-determined region of the body for drug emission and absorption.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Principles relating to route of administration, metabolism, site of specific targeting, and toxicity are most important within this field.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Drugs administered orally (through mouth) are usually encapsulated in some structure in order to protect the drug from immune and biological responses.
[src:allose/amylopectin] These structures aim to keep the drug intact until its site of action and release it at a correct dosage when exposed to a specific marker.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Corn and potato starch are often used for this as they contain 60-80% amylopectin.
[src:allose/amylopectin] They are mostly used in solid preparations: powders, granules, capsules, and tablets.
[src:allose/amylopectin] As a natural polysaccharide, it has a compatible nature with anatomical structures and molecules.
[src:allose/amylopectin] This prevents any sort of negative immune response, which is a highly controversial topic in drug delivery.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Biodegradability of starch allows it to keep the drug intact until reaching its site of action.
[src:allose/amylopectin] This allows the drug to avoid low pH situations such as the digestive system.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Native starch can also be modified in physical, chemical, and enzymatic ways to improve mechanical or biochemical properties.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Within drug delivery, physical modification include treatment under mechanical forces, heat, or pressure.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Chemical modifications attempt to alter molecular structure which can include breaking or addition of bonds.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Treating starch with enzymes can allow for increased water solubility.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Tissue engineering aims to generate functional constructs which could replace or improve damaged or infected tissues or whole organs.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Many of these constructs lead to infected tissue around the implant area.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Coating these materials in amylopectin allows reduction in this infectious reaction.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Since amylopectin is mainly used as a coating around these constructs in as it prevents following immune reactions.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Since amylopectin is derived directly from a natural polysaccharide, it integrates well with tissues and cells.
[src:allose/amylopectin] However, mechanical properties of amylopectin are not optimal due to its high level of crosslinking.
[src:allose/amylopectin] This can be avoided by the formation of amylopectin fibers or by forming a nanocomposite with another more rigid polymer.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin-based fibers have been fabricated mainly by blending native or modified starches with polymers, plasticizers, cross-linkers, or other additives.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Most amylopectin-based fibers are fabricated by electro-wet-spinning, however, the method is demonstrated to be suitable for starches with amylopectin content below 65% and sensitive to amylopectin content of starches.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Electrospinning allows for amylopectin to coagulate and form a filament.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Fibrous starches induce a more dense material, which can optimize the mechanical properties of starch.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Fibers in biomaterials can be used for bone tissue engineering as suitable environment for bone tissue repair and regeneration.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Natural bone is a complex composite material composed of an extracellular matrix of mineralized fibers containing living cells and bioactive molecules.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Consequently, the use of fibers in biomaterial-based scaffolds offers a wide variety of opportunities to replicate the functional performance of bone.
[src:allose/amylopectin] In the last decade, fiber-based techniques such as weaving, knitting, braiding, as well as electrospinning, and direct writing have emerged as promising platforms for making 3D tissue constructs.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Nanoscience and nanotechnology have been emerging as a technology for the development of various hybrid and composite materials for biomedical applications.
[src:allose/amylopectin] When nanomaterials are used for the development of the composites in biology, they are called bionanocomposites.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Bionanocomposites have been used in tissue engineering to replace, support, or regenerate the cells, organs, or parts of human entity such that it can function as normal.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin-based bionanocomposites are another important class of bionanomaterials, which are biodegradable, with higher mechanical properties, optical transparency, thermal stability, and barrier properties than thermoplastic starch.
[src:allose/amylopectin] Amylopectin is usually combined with a synthetic polymer with higher elastic modulus and yield strength.
[src:allose/amylopectin] This allows for starch to withstand the higher fluid flow and mechanical forces prevalent in bone, cardiac, and endothelial tissue.
[src:allose/amylose] Amylose is made up of α(1→4) bound glucose molecules.
[src:allose/amylose] The carbon atoms on glucose are numbered, starting at the aldehyde (C=O) carbon, so, in amylose, the 1-carbon on one glucose molecule is linked to the 4-carbon on the next glucose molecule (α(1→4) bonds).
[src:allose/amylose] The structural formula of amylose is pictured at right.
[src:allose/amylose] The number of repeated glucose subunits (n) is usually in the range of 300 to 3000, but can be many thousands.
[src:allose/amylose] There are three main forms of amylose chains can take.
[src:allose/amylose] It can exist in a disordered amorphous conformation, found both in starch granules and in hydrated amylose (when starch is cooked in water).
[src:allose/amylose] There are also two different helical forms.
[src:allose/amylose] Starting with purified amylose, it can bind with another amylose molecule in a double helix (A or B form), or it can bind with a guest molecule such as iodine, a fatty acid, or an aromatic compound, known as the V form.
[src:allose/amylose] Within this form, there are many different variations.
[src:allose/amylose] Each is notated with V and then a subscript indicating the number of glucose units per turn.
[src:allose/amylose] The most common is the V6 form, which has six glucose units a turn.
[src:allose/amylose] These provide an even larger space for the guest molecule to bind.
[src:allose/amylose] This linear structure can have some rotation around the phi and psi angles, but for the most part bound glucose ring oxygens lie on one side of the structure.
[src:allose/amylose] The α(1→4) structure promotes the formation of a helix structure, making it possible for hydrogen bonds to form between the oxygen atoms bound at the 2-carbon of one glucose molecule and the 3-carbon of the next glucose molecule.
[src:allose/amylose] Fiber X-ray diffraction analysis coupled with computer-based structure refinement has found A-, B-, and C- polymorphs of amylose.
[src:allose/amylose] Each form corresponds to either the A-, the B-, or the C- starch forms.
[src:allose/amylose] A- and B- structures have different helical crystal structures and water contents, whereas the C- structure is a mixture of A- and B- unit cells, resulting in an intermediate packing density between the two forms.
[src:allose/amylose] High-amylose forms of starch make it more resistant to digestion.
[src:allose/amylose] It also reduces the crystallinity of amylopectin and how easily water can infiltrate the starch.
[src:allose/amylose] The higher the amylose content, the less expansion potential and the lower the gel strength for the same starch concentration.
[src:allose/amylose] This can be countered partially by increasing the granule size.
[src:allose/amylose] Amylose is important in plant energy storage.
[src:allose/amylose] It is less readily digested than amylopectin.
[src:allose/amylose] It makes up about 30% of the stored starch in plants, though the percentage varies by species and variety.
[src:allose/amylose] The digestive enzyme α-amylase breaks down starch molecules into maltotriose and maltose, which can be used as sources of energy.
[src:allose/amylose] Amylose is also an important thickener, water binder, emulsion stabilizer, and gelling agent in industrial and food-based contexts.
[src:allose/amylose] Loose helical amylose chains have a hydrophobic interior that can bind to hydrophobic molecules such as lipids and aromatic compounds.
[src:allose/amylose] The one problem with this is that, when it crystallizes or associates, it can lose some stability, often releasing water in the process (syneresis).
[src:allose/amylose] When amylose concentration is increased, gel stickiness decreases but firmness increases.
[src:allose/amylose] When other things, including amylopectin, bind to amylose, the viscosity can be affected, but incorporating κ-carrageenan, alginate, xanthan gum, or low-molecular-weight sugars can reduce the loss in stability.
[src:allose/amylose] The ability to bind water can add substance to food, possibly serving as a fat replacement.
[src:allose/amylose] For example, amylose is responsible for causing white sauce to thicken, but, upon cooling, the solid and the water will partly separate.
[src:allose/amylose] Amylose is known for its good film-forming properties, useful in food packaging.
[src:allose/amylose] Excellent film-forming behavior of amylose was studied already in 1950s.
[src:allose/amylose] Amylose films are better for both barrier properties and mechanical properties when compared to the amylopectin films.
[src:allose/amylose] In a laboratory setting, it can act as a marker.
[src:allose/amylose] Iodine molecules fit neatly inside the helical structure of amylose, binding with the starch polymer that absorbs certain known wavelengths of light.
[src:allose/amylose] Hence, a common test is the iodine test for starch.
[src:allose/amylose] If starch is mixed with a small amount of yellow iodine solution, a blue-black color will be observed.
[src:allose/amylose] The intensity of the color can be tested with a colorimeter, using a red filter to discern the concentration of starch present in the solution.
[src:allose/amylose] It is also possible to use starch as an indicator in titrations involving iodine reduction.
[src:allose/amylose] It is also used in amylose magnetic beads and resin to separate maltose-binding protein.
[src:allose/amylose] High-amylose varieties of rice, the less sticky long-grain rice, have a much lower glycemic load, which could be beneficial for diabetics.
[src:allose/amylose] Researchers have identified the Granule Bound Starch Synthase (GBSS) as the enzyme that specifically elongates amylose during starch biosynthesis in plants.
[src:allose/amylose] The waxy locus in maize encodes for the GBSS protein.
[src:allose/amylose] Mutants lacking the GBSS protein produce starch containing only amylopectin, such as in waxy corn.
[src:allose/amylose] In Arabidopsis leaves, another gene, encoding the Protein Targeting to STarch (PTST) protein, is required in addition to GBSS for amylose synthesis.
[src:allose/amylose] Mutants lacking either protein produce starch without amylose.
[src:allose/amylose] Genetically modified potato cultivar Amflora by BASF Plant Science was developed to not produce amylose.
[src:allose/anomer] In carbohydrate chemistry, **anomers** (from Greek *ἄνω* 'up, above' and *μέρος* 'part') are specific types of stereoisomers found in sugars.
[src:allose/anomer] Many common sugars, such as glucose, exist in both a linear (or open-chain) form and a cyclic (or ring) form.
[src:allose/anomer] The ring is formed when one end of the sugar molecule connects to the other end.
[src:allose/anomer] The carbon atom where this ring closure occurs is called the **anomeric carbon**.
[src:allose/anomer] Depending on the direction from which the connection is made, this anomeric carbon can have its new group (–OH) pointing in one of two distinct orientations, typically visualized as "up" or "down" in a standard diagram.
[src:allose/anomer] These two resulting molecules are the anomers.
[src:allose/anomer] More formally, an anomer is an epimer at the hemiacetal/hemiketal carbon atom in a cyclic saccharide.
[src:allose/anomer] The process of one anomer converting to the other is known as **anomerization**.
[src:allose/anomer] For the reducing sugars present in biology, this process is known as mutarotation, catalyzed by dilute acid or base.
[src:allose/anomer] Because they have different three-dimensional structures, anomers have distinct physical properties, such as melting point and specific rotation.
[src:allose/anomer] Every two anomers are designated alpha (α) or beta (β), according to the configurational relationship between the *anomeric centre* and the *anomeric reference atom*, hence they are relative stereodescriptors.
[src:allose/anomer] The anomeric centre in hemiacetals is the anomeric carbon C-1; in hemiketals, it is the carbon derived from the carbonyl of the ketone (e.g.
[src:allose/anomer] In aldohexoses the anomeric reference atom is the stereocenter that is farthest from the anomeric carbon in the ring (the configurational atom, defining the sugar as D or L).
[src:allose/anomer] For example, in α-D-glucopyranose the reference atom is C-5.
[src:allose/anomer] If in the cyclic Fischer projection the exocyclic oxygen atom at the anomeric centre is cis (on the same side) to the exocyclic oxygen attached to the anomeric reference atom (in the OH group) the anomer is β.
[src:allose/anomer] If the two oxygens are trans (on different sides) the anomer is α.
[src:allose/anomer] Anomerization is the process of conversion of one anomer to the other.
[src:allose/anomer] For reducing sugars, anomerization is referred to as *mutarotation* and occurs readily in solution and is catalyzed by acid and base.
[src:allose/anomer] This reversible process typically leads to an anomeric mixture in which eventually an equilibrium is reached between the two single anomers.
[src:allose/anomer] The ratio of the two anomers is specific for a given sugar solution.
[src:allose/anomer] For example, regardless of the configuration of the starting D-glucose, a solution will gradually move towards being a mixture of approximately 64% β-D-glucopyranoside and 36% of α-D-glucopyranose.
[src:allose/anomer] As the ratio changes, the optical rotation of the mixture changes; this phenomenon is called mutarotation.
[src:allose/anomer] While enantiomers have equal and opposite specific rotations, anomers (which are diastereomers) do not follow this rule and can have different specific rotations both in magnitude and sign.
[src:allose/anomer] The values for specific rotation are reported in units of deg·cm3·g−1·dm−1, which are typically shortened to just degrees, wherein the other components of the unit are tacitly assumed.
[src:allose/anomer] The amount of anomers present in the equilibrium mixture can be found if the specific rotations of the mixture $[\alpha ]_{m}$ and the individual pure anomers $[\alpha ]_{i}$ are known.
[src:allose/anomer] Though the cyclic forms of sugars are usually heavily favoured, hemiacetals in aqueous solution are in equilibrium with their open-chain forms.
[src:allose/anomer] In aldohexoses this equilibrium is established as the hemiacetal bond between C-1 (the carbon bound to two oxygens) and the C-5 oxygen.
[src:allose/anomer] It is cleaved (forming the open-chain compound) and reformed (forming the cyclic compound).
[src:allose/anomer] When the hemiacetal group is reformed, the OH group on C-5 may attack either of the two stereochemically distinct sides of the aldehyde group on C-1.
[src:allose/anomer] Which side it attacks on determines whether the α- or β-anomer is formed.
[src:allose/anomer] Anomerization of glycosides typically occurs under acidic conditions.
[src:allose/anomer] Typically, anomerization occurs through protonation of the exocyclic acetal oxygen, ionization to form an oxocarbenium ion with release of an alcohol, and nucleophilic attack by an alcohol on the reverse face of the oxocarbenium ion, followed by deprotonation.
[src:allose/anomer] Anomers are different in structure, and thus have different stabilizing and destabilizing effects from each other.
[src:allose/anomer] For D-glucopyranoside, the β-anomer is the more stable anomer in water.
[src:allose/anomer] For D-mannopyranose, the α-anomer is the more stable anomer.
[src:allose/anomer] Because anomers are diastereomers of each other, they often differ in physical and chemical properties.
[src:allose/anomer] One of the most important physical properties that is used to study anomers is the specific rotation, which can be monitored by polarimetry.
